div.font:
Note:
A product family is expected to have two sets of attributes: shared attributes that cover all products in the family, and an attribute map that contains the POSSIBLE attributes a product can set.
Example:
A series of gaming mice may share the same sensors, but come in different sizes, finishes etc.
shared_attributes -> { 'sensor': 'Pixar 3380' }
attribute_map -> { 'size': ['large', 'small'], 'color': ['black', 'red'] } (in family)
defined_attributes -> { 'size': 'large', 'color': 'red' } (a product in that family)

div.div: Prices have fluctuation, and this is meant to encapsulate that. Current prices are typically not marked with a `to`, and is intended to be updated.
Might be odd for discounts, which typically only have a set duration for eligibility. Might have to introduce some sort of precedence. (e.g: discounts take place before normal prices)
In addition: products can be given a price guidance, checking that the pricing of a product is aligned with the price guidances of each of those products might be a good idea.
